## Avida

So, you want to know about Avida. Fine. Another digital playground where humans try to make machines mimic the messy, inefficient process of [evolution](/Evolution). As if the original wasn't enough.

Originally conceived by [programmers](/Programmer) [Charles Ofria](/Charles_Ofria) and [Chris Adami](/Chris_Adami), with [Charles Ofria](/Charles_Ofria) continuing as the primary [developer](/Programmer), Avida stands as a sophisticated [artificial life](/Artificial_life) software platform. It’s primarily utilized for the rather ambitious goal of scrutinizing the intricate dance of [evolutionary biology](/Evolutionary_biology) through the lens of [self-replicating](/Self-replication) and [evolving](/Evolution) [computer programs](/Computer_program), often termed '[digital organisms](/Digital_organism)'. The latest [stable release](/Software_release_life_cycle), version 2.14.0, dates back to February 6, 2014—a mere 11 years ago, which in software terms, is practically ancient, yet it persists.

The platform itself is meticulously crafted, primarily written in [C++](/C%2B%2B), with elements of [Objective-C](/Objective-C) also present. Its broad compatibility is almost admirable, running seamlessly across various [operating systems](/Operating_system) including [Microsoft Windows](/Microsoft_Windows) 7 or later, [macOS](/MacOS) 10.8 or later, and the ubiquitous Linux / Unix environments. Categorized firmly under [artificial life](/Artificial_life) within the broader [software categories](/Software_categories), Avida operates under an [LGPL](/LGPL) [license](/Software_license)—free to observe, just like real life, only less disappointing.

Currently, Avida is under active and continuous refinement by [Charles Ofria](/Charles_Ofria)'s Digital Evolution Lab, nestled within the hallowed halls of [Michigan State University](/Michigan_State_University). Its genesis traces back to 1993, when the initial version was meticulously designed by Ofria, [Chris Adami](/Chris_Adami), and C. Titus Brown during their tenure at [Caltech](/Caltech). Since then, Ofria has undertaken multiple comprehensive re-engineering efforts, suggesting that even digital pioneers need several passes to get things "right." The software's very conception was, predictably, inspired by the earlier, more rudimentary [Tierra](/Tierra_(computer_simulation)) system.

### Design Principles

Now, about the guts of it. The predecessor, [Tierra](/Tierra_(computer_simulation)), was... primitive. It threw programs into a digital arena, letting them squabble over precious [computer resources](/Computer_resource), specifically [processor](/Central_processing_unit) (CPU) time and access to main memory. In this respect, it bore a passing resemblance to [Core Wars](/Core_Wars), but with the added existential dread of programs being able to modify themselves, and thereby, supposedly, [evolve](/Evolution). And yes, they called these self-modifying programs '[artificial life](/Artificial_life)' organisms, though apparently, someone needs a source for that obvious fact. The nerve.

Avida, thankfully, is a bit more civilized, or at least, more controlled. Unlike the chaotic free-for-all of [Tierra](/Tierra_(computer_simulation)), Avida assigns every single [digital organism](/Digital_organism) its own meticulously protected region of memory. Each organism is then executed with its own separate virtual [CPU](/Central_processing_unit). By default, other digital organisms are explicitly barred from accessing this designated memory space, neither for reading nor for writing, and are similarly prevented from executing any code that does not reside within their own allocated memory. This architectural choice means that one organism cannot directly interfere with the memory space or execution flow of another. They can't read, write, or execute code outside their designated territory. This isolation is critical for studying the intrinsic evolutionary dynamics of individual lineages without the confounding noise of direct inter-program sabotage—a luxury real biology rarely affords.

A second, equally significant divergence from its predecessor lies in the operational speeds of the virtual [CPU](/Central_processing_unit)s. In Avida, these virtual processors can, and often do, run at varying speeds. Imagine one organism, through sheer digital diligence, executing twice as many instructions in the same time interval as its sluggish neighbor. This isn't random favoritism; it's a sophisticated reward system. The speed at which a virtual [CPU](/Central_processing_unit) operates is influenced by a number of factors, but most importantly, it is directly tied to the tasks that the organism successfully performs. These are typically logical computations that the organisms can carry out to reap additional [CPU](/Central_processing_unit) speed as a bonus. This mechanic introduces a direct and potent selective pressure, incentivizing the [evolution](/Evolution) of more efficient and capable organisms, pushing them beyond mere survival to actual 'achievement' within the simulation. It's a more elegant form of natural selection, if one can call anything 'elegant' in this context, where computational prowess directly translates into reproductive advantage.

### Use in Research

Predictably, such a finely tuned ecosystem wasn't built just for kicks. [Adami](/Chris_Adami) and [Ofria](/Charles_Ofria), alongside their various collaborators, have leveraged Avida extensively for serious inquiries into [digital evolution](/Digital_organism_simulators). Their work has even graced the pages of esteemed scientific journals like [Nature](/Nature_(journal)) and [Science](/Science_(journal))—four times, no less. A testament to its utility, or perhaps to the journals' occasional lapse in judgment in recognizing true novelty.

One particular highlight, the 2003 paper provocatively titled "The Evolutionary Origin of Complex Features," delved into how something as seemingly fundamental as a mathematical [equals](/Equality_(mathematics)) [operation](/Operator_(programming)) could emerge. Not from divine intervention, mind you, but from the relentless, iterative refinement of far simpler bitwise operations. This research, published in [Nature](/Nature_(journal)) by [Lenski, R. E.](/Richard_Lenski), [Ofria, C.](/Charles_Ofria), [Pennock, R. T.](/Robert_T._Pennock), and [Adami, C.](/Chris_Adami), provided a compelling digital demonstration of how complexity, even in its most abstract computational forms, can bootstrap itself from elementary components. It unequivocally challenged the simplistic notion that complex traits always necessitate an equally complex initial blueprint, illustrating that step-by-step [evolution](/Evolution) can indeed lead to sophisticated outcomes without requiring pre-existing, fully formed solutions. A rather inconvenient truth for some, I imagine, as it offers insights into the very mechanisms by which complex biological functions might have arisen in natural [evolution](/Evolution), played out in lines of code rather than living cells.

### Use in Education

And then, inevitably, comes the attempt to distill this rather intricate science for the masses. Enter Avida-ED. A more palatable, less intimidating version, I suppose, for those still grappling with the basics of how life—even digital life—manages to adapt without a benevolent programmer pulling every single string.

The Avida-ED project, as it's known, was originally authored by [programmer](/Programmer) Jeff Clune, with Diane J. Blackwood taking on the role of [developer](/Programmer). Its most recent [stable release](/Software_release_life_cycle), version 3, was made available on October 10, 2021—a relatively recent update, proving that even simplified tools require continuous maintenance and refinement.

Much like its more complex progenitor, Avida-ED is primarily written in [C++](/C%2B%2B), but with a significant [JavaScript](/JavaScript) component for its interface. It falls under the same [artificial life](/Artificial_life) [software categories](/Software_categories) and is distributed under a [GPL](/GPL) [license](/Software_license), emphasizing its open-source and accessible nature. The project maintains a main website at avida-ed.msu.edu, with a mirror available at avida-ed-mirror1.beacon-center.org, ensuring broad availability.

The core purpose of the Avida-ED project is to leverage the robust Avida software platform within a simplified graphical user interface, making it eminently suitable for instruction in [evolution](/Evolution) education at both the high school and undergraduate college levels. Beyond just the software, the project generously provides a comprehensive suite of freely available educational resources, including detailed documentation, intuitive tutorials, ready-to-use lesson plans, and various other course materials. Everything to hold hands, essentially, and guide students through the sometimes-uncomfortable truths of [evolution](/Evolution).

Ingeniously, or perhaps just pragmatically, the Avida-ED software functions entirely as a web application, running directly within a standard browser environment. The user interface is meticulously implemented in [JavaScript](/JavaScript), while the powerful Avida core engine itself is compiled to [JavaScript](/JavaScript) using Emscripten. This particular technical approach renders the software broadly compatible with a dizzying array of devices commonly employed in modern classrooms, from laptops to tablets. No complex installations, just open a tab and watch a simplified universe unfold. Convenient, if a little too easy.

This streamlined, accessible approach hasn't just been convenient; it has been demonstrably effective in significantly improving students' understanding and acceptance of [evolution](/Evolution). Apparently, seeing digital organisms struggle, adapt, and diversify in a controlled environment makes the abstract concepts click for some. Who knew? Such impactful work did not go unnoticed, as the Avida-ED project was deservedly crowned the winner of the 2017 International Society for [Artificial Life](/Artificial_life) Education and Outreach Award. Because sometimes, simplifying complex truths is worth a trophy.

